name: Robinswood Hill Perry Pears
description: Scattered across the lower slopes of the hill are ancient perry pear and apple trees, remnants of old farm orchards.

name: Alney Island Wild Garlic
description: The damp, wooded areas of this river island are thick with wild garlic in the spring months.

name: Incredible Edible Gloucester - Gate Streets
description: Public planters located around the Cross and the four main 'Gate Streets' featuring rosemary, sage, and mint.

name: Saintbridge Allotment Orchard Fringe
description: A selection of apple and damson trees located on the public-facing edge of the allotment site.

name: Glevum Way Hazelnuts
description: The green corridors and balancing ponds in Abbeydale are lined with hazel trees and elder.

name: Gloucester Sharpness Canal Blackberries
description: Miles of blackberry bushes line the canal path heading south towards Rea Bridge.

name: Barnwood Park Walnuts
description: The arboretum area of the park contains several mature walnut and sweet chestnut trees.

name: Horsbere Brook Wild Greens
description: Find wild sorrel and watermint in the flood alleviation meadows surrounding the brook.

name: Matson Incredible Edible Planters
description: Planters located near the local shops and library featuring hardy winter greens and summer strawberries.

name: Llanthony Secunda Elder
description: Elder bushes grow along the edges of the historic priory grounds and the canal-side path.

name: Cotswold Fringe Sloes
description: The bridleways heading up toward Cooper's Hill are rich with blackthorn bushes (sloes).

name: Kingsway Community Orchard
description: Young but productive community-managed orchard featuring various apple varieties.

name: Lower Severn Estuary Sea Beet
description: Wild sea beet can be found on the river banks near Elmore (take care with tidal Bore).

name: Gloucester Park Rosehips
description: Wild rose bushes in the perimeter shrubbery provide a decent crop of hips in late autumn.

name: Over Farm Trail Blackberries
description: The public footpaths through the floodplains toward Over are thick with berries.
